In [[Ireland]], [[city|the term ''city'']] has somewhat differing meanings in [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]].

Historically, [[city status in the United Kingdom]], and before that in the [[Kingdom of Ireland]], was a ceremonial designation. It carried more prestige than the alternative municipal titles "[[borough]]", "[[town]]" and "[[township]]", but gave no extra legal powers. This remains the case in Northern Ireland, which is still part of the [[United Kingdom]]. In the Republic of Ireland, "city" has an additional designation [[local government in the Republic of Ireland|in local government]].

==History up to 1920==
Before the [[Partition of Ireland]] in 1920–22, the island formed a single jurisdiction in which "city" had a common history.

The first edition of the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' s.v. ''city'' (published 1893), explains that in England, from the time of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]], the word was applied to towns with [[List of cathedrals in the United Kingdom#Church of England|Church of England cathedrals]]. It goes on to say:
<blockquote>The history of the word in Ireland is somewhat parallel. Probably all or most of the places having bishops have been styled on some occasion ''civitas''; but some of these are mere hamlets, and the term 'city' is currently applied only to a few of them which are ancient and important boroughs. [[Thom's Directory]] applies it to [[Dublin]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Derry]], [[Limerick]] ('City of [[Treaty of Limerick|the violated treaty]]'), [[Kilkenny]], and [[Waterford]]; also to [[Armagh]] and [[Cashel, County Tipperary|Cashel]], but not to [[Tuam]] or [[Galway]] (though the latter is often called 'the City of [[Tribes of Galway|the Tribes]]'). [[Belfast]] was, in 1888, created a 'city' by Royal Letters Patent.</blockquote>

===''Cathair''===
In most European languages, there is no distinction between "city" and "town", with the same word translating both English words; for example, ''ville'' in French, or ''Stadt'' in German.

In [[Modern Irish]], "city" is translated ''cathair''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.ie/AdvSearch.aspx?wording=city&extent=complete&length=both&lang=1&posL2=5&posLX=5&domain=0&collection=0 |title=city |work=[[Focal (lexicographical website)|Focal]] |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and "town" is translated ''baile'';<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focal.ie/AdvSearch.aspx?wording=town&extent=complete&length=both&lang=1&posL2=0&posLX=5&domain=0&collection=0 |title=town |work=[[Focal (lexicographical website)|Focal]] |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> however, this is a recent convention; previously ''baile'' was applied to any settlement,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dil.ie/results-list.asp?mode=ADV&searchText=%20baile&HIGH=%20baile&respage=0&resperpage=1&Fuzzy=0&bhcp=1|title=baile|work=Electronic Dictionary of the Irish Language|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|accessdate=17 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> while ''cathair'' meant a walled or stone [[fortress]], [[monastery]], or city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dil.ie/results-list.asp?mode=ADV&searchText=%20cathair&HIGH=%20cathair&respage=0&resperpage=1&Fuzzy=0&bhcp=1|title=cathair|work=Electronic Dictionary of the Irish Language|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|accessdate=17 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> For example, Dublin, long the metropolis of the island, has been called ''Baile Átha Cliath'' since the fifteenth century,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/Eolas/Data/Brainse/Dublin.pdf |page=6 |format=PDF |title=Dublin, the history of the placename |publisher=The Placenames Branch |language=Irish, English |accessdate=16 May 2010 |quote=The element baile, 'town', was prefixed to the name some time in the 15th century |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614200352/http://www.logainm.ie/eolas/Data/Brainse/Dublin.pdf |archivedate=14 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> while its earliest city charter is from 1172.<ref name="comm1835-dub"/> The Irish text of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] translates "city of Dublin" as ''cathair Bhaile Átha Chliath'',<ref name="Cearúil">{{cite book |url=https://www.constitution.ie/Documents/Bunreacht%20na%20hEireann%20-%20Study%20of%20the%20Irish%20Text.pdf |accessdate=9 September 2013 |format=PDF|last1=Ó Cearúil|first1=Micheál |last2=Ó Murchú|first2=Máirtín |others=for the All-Party Oireachtas Committee on the Constitution|title= Bunreacht na hÉireann: A study of the Irish text|year=1999|publisher=Stationery Office|location=Dublin |isbn=0-7076-6400-4|pages=172–3, 225–6}}</ref> combining the modern sense of ''cathair'' with the historic sense of ''Baile''.  Conversely, the original Irish names of such smaller settlements as [[Cahir]], [[Cahirciveen]], [[Caherdaniel]], or [[Westport, County Mayo|Westport]] (''Cathair na Mart'') use ''cathair'' in the older sense.

===''Civitas''===
{{See also|List of cathedrals in Ireland}}
In the [[Roman Empire]], the Latin ''[[civitas]]'' referred originally to the jurisdiction of a capital town, typically the territory of a single conquered tribe.<ref name="Galinie">{{cite book|editor1-last=Vauchez|editor1-first=André|editor2-last=Dobson|editor2-first=Richard Barrie|editor3-last=Lapidge|editor3-first=Michael|first=Henri|last=Galinié|title=Encyclopedia of the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qtgotOF0MKQC&pg=PA313|accessdate=17 May 2010|year=2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-57958-282-1|page=313|chapter=''Civitas'', City}}</ref> Later it came to mean the capital town itself.<ref name="Galinie"/> When [[Gallo-Roman culture#Christianity|Christianity was organised in Gaul]], each [[diocese]] was the territory of a tribe, and each bishop resided in the ''civitas''.<ref name="Galinie"/> Thus ''civitas'' came to mean the site of a cathedral.<ref name="Galinie"/> This usage carried over generally to [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] ''cité'' and English ''city'' in England. [[William Blackstone]]'s ''[[Commentaries on the Laws of England]]'' of 1765<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30802/30802-h/30802-h.htm#Page_111 |title=Commentaries on the Laws of England |volume=1 |chapter=Introduction §4: Of the Countries subject to the Laws of England |first=William |last=Blackstone |page=111 |year=1765 |publisher=[[Clarendon Press]] |location=Oxford |accessdate=17 May 2010}}</ref> cites [[Edward Coke]]'s ''[[Institutes of the Lawes of England]]'' of 1634:<ref name="CokeLittleton1853">{{cite book|last1=Coke|first1=Edward|authorlink1=Edward Coke|last2=Hale|first2=Matthew|authorlink2=Matthew Hale (jurist)|last3=Nottingham|first3=Heneage Finch, Earl of |authorlink3=Heneage Finch, 1st Earl of Nottingham|author4=Francis Hargrave, Charles Butler|title=A commentary upon Littleton |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GOgKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA163|accessdate=17 May 2010|edition=1st American, from 19th London|series=The Institutes of the laws of England|volume=1|year=1853|publisher=R. H. Small|location=Philadelphia |pages=Vol. 1 pp.163–5|nopp=Y|chapter=109b}}</ref>
<blockquote>A city is a town incorporated, which is or hath been the see of a bishop; and though the bishoprick be dissolved, [[Diocese of Westminster (Church of England)|as at Westminster]], yet still it remaineth a city.</blockquote>
Subsequent legal authorities disputed this assertion; pointing out that the [[City of Westminster]] gained its status not implicitly from [[Westminster Abbey|its (former) cathedral]] but explicitly from [[letters patent]] issued by [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] shortly after the Diocese was established.<ref name="CokeLittleton1853"/>

In any case it was moot whether the association of ''city'' with dioceses applied to Ireland.  A 1331 writ of [[Edward III of England|Edward III]] is addressed, among others, to "Civibus civitatis Dublin, —de Droghda, – de Waterford, de Cork, – de Limrik" implying ''civitas'' status for [[Drogheda]].<ref>Gale 1834, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3uQSAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR252 Appendix p.cclii]</ref> Some credence to the episcopal connection was given by the 1835 Report of the Commissioners into Municipal Corporations in Ireland<ref name="Armagh-burgesses"/><ref name="Tuam-burgesses"/> and the 1846 ''Parliamentary Gazetteer of Ireland'' (see [[#ParlGazz|below]]).

Whereas the Normans moved many English sees from a rural location to a regional hub, the cathedrals of the established [[Church of Ireland]] remained at the often rural sites agreed at the twelfth-century [[Synod of Rathbreasail]] and [[Synod of Kells]].  The [[Roman Catholicism in Ireland|Roman Catholic church in Ireland]] had no cathedrals during the [[Protestant Ascendancy]].

[[Downpatrick]] is noted as "the City of Down" is a 1403 record, although no granting instrument is known.<ref name="comm1835-downpatrick"/> The Corporation was defunct by 1661, when [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] initiated plans to revive it, which were not completed.<ref name="comm1835-downpatrick"/>

Although the charter of  [[Clogher]] did not describe it as a city, the [[borough constituency]] in the [[Irish House of Commons]] was officially called "[[Clogher (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|City of Clogher]]".<ref name="comm1835-Clogher">Rep Comm Mun Corp Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=YdVbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA997 pp.997–998]</ref> It was a [[pocket borough]] of the [[Bishop of Clogher]], disestablished by the [[Acts of Union 1800]].<ref name="comm1835-Clogher"/>

John Caillard Erck records of [[Old Leighlin]], "So flourishing indeed was this town in subsequent times, that it received the appellation of the city of Leighlin, and was inhabited by eighty-six burgesses during the prelacy of Richard Rocomb, who died in 1420."<ref name="Erck1827">{{cite book|last=Erck|first=John Caillard|title=The ecclesiastical register: containing the names of the dignitaries and parochial clergy of Ireland : as also of the parishes and their respective patrons and an account of monies granted for building churches and glebe-houses with ecclesiastical annals annexed to each diocese and appendixes : containing among other things several cases of quare impedit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mXcrAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA128|accessdate=14 May 2010|year=1827|publisher=R. Milliken and Son|page=128}}</ref>

===Royal charters===
For seven settlements in Ireland (listed [[#List|below]]), the title "city" was historically conferred by the awarding of a [[royal charter]] which used the word "city" in the name of the [[body corporate]] charged with governing the settlement. (In fact, charters were for centuries written in Latin, with ''civitas'' denoting "city" and ''villa'' "town".) [[Armagh]] had no charter recognising it as a city but claimed the title by [[Custom (law)|prescription]]; acts of the [[Parliament of Ireland]] in 1773 and 1791 refer to the "city of Armagh".<ref>[http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=display_bill&id=3048 13 & 14 George III c.40] and [http://www.qub.ac.uk/ild/?func=display_bill&id=2306 31 George III c.46]</ref>

The label "city" carried prestige but was purely ceremonial and did not in practice affect the municipal government.  However, a section of the [[Newtown Act]] of 1748<ref>21 Geo. II c.10 s.8</ref> allowed for members of a Corporation to be non-resident of its municipality in the case of "any town corporate or borough, not being a city".<ref name="comm-1747">Rept Comm Mun Corp Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=c9VbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA19 pp.19–20]</ref> This was enacted because there were too few Protestants in smaller towns to make up the numbers.<ref name="comm-1747"/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Malcomson |first=A. P. W. |date=March 1973 |title=The Newtown Act of 1748: Revision and Reconstruction |journal=Irish Historical Studies |publisher=Irish Historical Studies Publications |volume=18 |issue=71 |pages=313–344 |jstor=30005420}}</ref> The 1835 Report of the Commissioners on Municipal Corporations in Ireland questioned whether it was applicable in the case of [[Armagh]] and [[Tuam]], both being episcopal sees and hence "cities" in Blackstone's definition. In fact, non-residents had served on both corporations.<ref name="Armagh-burgesses">Rep Comm Mun Corp Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=lksSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA671 p.671–2 "City of Armagh" §10]</ref><ref name="Tuam-burgesses">Rep Comm Mun Corp Irl [http://pdf.library.soton.ac.uk/EPPI/13040-7.pdf#page=14 p.432 "Borough of Tuam" §13]</ref>

There is one reference in [[James VI and I|James I]]'s 1609 charter for [[Wexford]] to "our said city of Wexford", but the rest of the charter describes it as a town or borough.<ref>Gale 1834, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3uQSAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR83 Appendix 27: Translation from enrolment in Chancery of the charter to the town of Wexford by James the First; pp.83–4]</ref>

===After the Union===
After the [[Acts of Union 1800]], Ireland was part of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]], and British law governed the award and removal of the title "city".

The [[Municipal Corporations (Ireland) Act 1840]] abolished both those corporations which were already ''de facto'' defunct and those which were most egregiously unrepresentative. The latter category included Armagh and Cashel. It was moot whether these ''ipso facto'' were no longer cities; some later sources continued to describe them as such.

Prior to the [[Local Government (Ireland) Act 1898]], eight Irish municipalities were [[county corporate|counties corporate]].  This was distinct from being a city. Five of the eight were "County of the City", the other three being "County of the Town". The other cities —[[Derry]], and until 1840 Cashel and Armagh— were not governed separately from their surrounding counties; however, the official name of [[County Londonderry]] was for long "the City and County of Londonderry".

====The ''Parliamentary Gazetteer of Ireland''====
{{anchor|ParlGazz}}
The 1846 ''Parliamentary Gazetteer of Ireland'' uses the label "city" in a variety of ways. For [[Cork (city)|Cork]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA519 Vol.1 p.519 "Cork"] "A sea-port, a parliamentary borough, a city, the assize-town of the county of Cork, the capital of Munster, and the second town of Ireland"</ref> [[Dublin]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA108 Vol.2 p.108 "Dublin"] "The metropolis of Ireland, the second city of the British empire, and the seventh city of Europe"</ref> [[Kilkenny]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA431 Vol.2 p.431 "Kilkenny"] "A post and market town, a municipal and parliamentary borough, a city, the capital of the county of Kilkenny, and the seat of the diocese of Ossory"</ref> [[Limerick]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA632 Vol.2 p.632 "Limerick"] "A post, market, and sea-port town and borough, a city, and the capital of Western Munster"</ref> [[Derry]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA672 Vol.2 p.672 "Londonderry"] "A post, market, and sea-port town, a borough, a city, the county town of Londonderry, and the capital of the extreme north of Ulster"</ref> and [[Waterford]],<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=1HMuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA488 Vol.3 p.488 "Waterford"] "A post and market town, a sea-port, a borough, a city, and the capital of the county of Waterford"</ref> the definition at the start of the relevant article includes "a city". [[Armagh]] is defined as "[a] post, market, and ancient town, a [[royal borough]], the capital of a county, and the [[Metropolis (religious jurisdiction)|ecclesiastical metropolis]] of Ireland"; however it is called a "city" throughout its article.<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA78 Vol.1 p.78 "Armagh"]</ref> [[Cashel, County Tipperary|Cashel]] is treated similarly to Armagh.<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA342 Vol.1 p.342 "Cashel"] "A post and market town, a borough, an episcopal city, and the ecclesiastical metropolis of the southern province of Ireland"</ref> For other episcopal seats, "city" is not used, or used in hedged descriptions like "episcopal city",<ref name="pg-Clogher">1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA418 Vol.1 p.418 "Clogher"] "An ancient episcopal city and incorporated town, but at present a mere village"</ref><ref name="pg-Cloyne">1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA470 Vol.1 p.470 "Cloyne"] "A market and post town, and an ancient Episcopal city"</ref> "ancient city",<ref name="pg-Clogher"/><ref name="pg-Cloyne"/><ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA56 Vol.1 p.56 "Ardfert"] "This ancient and once important city is now a poor and declining village"</ref><ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA176 Vol.2 p.176 "Emly"] "Though now a mere village, it is noticed by some ancient historians as in their day a large and flourishing city."</ref> or "nominal city".<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=9rblf03SdkYC&pg=PA493 Vol.1 p.493 "Connor"] "the farce of nominal city character"</ref><ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA77 Vol.2 p.77 "Dromore"] "Though nominally a city, it is really but a small and common-place market-town."</ref> Of [[Kilfenora]] it says, "It belongs to the same category as [[Emly]], [[Clonfert]], [[Kilmacduagh]], [[Ardfert]], [[Connor, County Antrim|Connor]], Clogher, [[Kilmore, County Cavan|Kilmore]], [[Ferns, County Wexford|Ferns]], and [[Achonry]], in exhibiting a shrunk and ghastly caricature upon the practical notion of a 'city;' and nothing but its episcopal name and historical associations prevent it from being regarded as a mean and shabby hamlet."<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA409 Vol.2 p.409]</ref> Of [[Elphin, County Roscommon|Elphin]] it says "the general tone of at once masonry, manners, and business, is a hideous satire upon the idea of 'a city.'"<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA174 Vol.2 p.174]</ref> Of [[Downpatrick]] it says "it displays a striking, and almost outré combination of unique and common place character, of ancient piles and modern edifices curiously mingling the features of city and village, of political grandeur and social littleness."<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA60 Vol.2 p.60]</ref> There are passing references in other articles to "the city of [[Tuam]]",<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=1HMuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA398 Vol.3 p.398 "Tuam"] "The Clare and the Dunmore sections contain the city of Tuam"</ref> and "the city of [[Killaloe, County Clare|Killaloe]]".<ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA552 Vol.2 p.552 "Kincora"] "1 mile north-northwest of the city of Killaloe"</ref><ref>1846 Parl Gaz Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=1HMuAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA251 Vol.3 p.251 "Slieve Bernagh"] "it soars gradually up in the western vicinity of the city of Killaloe"</ref>

====Belfast====
Belfast in 1887 applied to be granted city status on the occasion of [[Queen Victoria]]'s [[Golden Jubilee]].<ref name="beckett44">Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA44 p.44]</ref> The [[Home Office]] objected to setting a precedent for granting city status to towns not episcopal sees.<ref name="beckett45">Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA45 p.45]</ref> [[Thomas Sexton (Irish politician)|Thomas Sexton]] asked in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]:<ref>{{cite hansard |title=Civil Services |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1887/jul/15/civil-services#column_977 |house=HC |column-start=977 |column-end=978 |date=15 July 1887 |volume=317 }}</ref>
<blockquote>with regard to the granting of the City Charter to Belfast. A Question was lately put in the House upon the subject, and ... [ [[William Henry Smith (1825–1891)|W. H. Smith]]] replied ... that the Government did not intend to recommend any such grant in connection with Her Majesty's Jubilee. ... I will ask him for a reply upon the point ... I do not know that there is much difference between a town and a city; but some people prefer the title of city, and if there is any advantage in a place being called a city, I think the people of Belfast are entitled to have their choice. There are eight cities in Ireland, and Belfast is next to Dublin in point of importance; according to Thom's information, it is the first town of manufacturing importance. I believe there is a strong desire that the title of city should be given to the place. ... It seems absurd that Belfast should be shut out from any City Charter, while Armagh, with 10,000 of a population, is a city; and when Cashell, with a population of 4,000, enjoys the distinction also. Perhaps the right hon. Gentleman the Chancellor of the Exchequer will be able to say that, in consideration of the importance of the town, the Government will recommend the Crown to grant to it the title of city. Like civility, a Charter of this kind costs nothing; and, therefore, I think that this Charter might be promptly and gracefully conceded to the town.</blockquote>

In 1888, the request was granted by [[letters patent]], setting a precedent for non-episcopal cities which was soon emulated by [[Dundee]] and [[Birmingham]].<ref>Beckett 2005, pp.45–50</ref>

==="Lord Mayor" and "Right Honourable"===
{{See also|List of lord mayoralties and lord provostships in the United Kingdom}}
The title [[Lord Mayor]] is given to the mayor of a privileged subset of UK cities. In some cases, a lord mayor additionally has the [[Style (manner of address)|style]] "[[Right Honourable]]".  The [[Lord Mayor of Dublin|Mayor of Dublin]] gained the title "lord" by a charter of 1641,<ref name="comm1835-1676">1835 Rep Comm Mun Corp Irl [https://books.google.com/books?id=YdVbAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA5 Vol 9 Pt 1 p.5]</ref><ref name="dcc-mayor">{{cite web|url=http://www.dublincity.ie/YOURCOUNCIL/LORDMAYORDUBLIN/HISTORYOFLORDMAYOR/Pages/HistoryLordMayorsOffice.aspx |title=History of the Lord Mayor's Office |publisher=Dublin City Council |accessdate=22 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419070445/http://www.dublincity.ie/YourCouncil/LordMayorDublin/HistoryofLordMayor/Pages/HistoryLordMayorsOffice.aspx |archivedate=19 April 2010 |df= }}</ref> but the [[Irish Confederate Wars|Confederate Wars]] and their aftermath meant the form "Lord Mayor" was not used till 1665.<ref name="dcc-mayor"/> The style "Right Honourable" was originally a consequence of the Lord Mayor's ''[[ex officio]]'' membership of the [[Privy Council of Ireland]]; it was later explicitly granted by the 1840 Act, and finally abolished by the [[Local Government Act 2001]].<ref>Local Government Act 2001 §32(3)b</ref> The [[Lord Mayor of Belfast]] gained the title in 1892 —based on the precedent of [[Dundee]]<ref>Beckett 2005 [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA67 p.67]</ref>— and the style "Right Honourable" in 1923, in recognition of Belfast's status as capital of the newly created [[Northern Ireland]]. The [[Lord Mayor of Cork]] gained the title in 1900, to mark [[Queen Victoria]]'s visit to Ireland;<ref>Beckett 2005 [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA68 p.68]</ref> the style "Right Honourable" has never applied. Armagh gained a lord mayor in 2012 for the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].<ref name="bbc17364651">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17364651|title=Three towns win city status for Diamond Jubilee|date=14 March 2012|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref>

==Northern Ireland==
{{main article|City status in the United Kingdom}}

===Armagh===
After [[Belfast]] received its charter in 1888, no further towns in nine-county [[Ulster]] applied for city status until 1953, when [[Armagh]] began to argue for the restoration of the status lost in 1840.<ref name="beckett133">Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA133 p.133]</ref> Its justification was that the [[Archbishop of Armagh]] was [[Primate of All Ireland]]. The council used the appellation "city" unofficially until 1994, when [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], announced the status had been granted to mark the 1,550th anniversary of the traditional date of Armagh's foundation by [[Saint Patrick]].<ref name="beckett134">Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA134 p.134]</ref>

===Lisburn and Newry===

[[Lisburn]] and [[Ballymena]] entered a UK-wide competition for city status held to mark the millennium in 2000; neither was selected, being below the unofficial 200,000 population threshold.<ref>Beckett 2005, pp.141–163</ref> Controversy surrounded the decision-making process for the competition, and as a result the rules changed for a 2002 competition for the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]], with [[Northern Ireland]] guaranteed one new city.<ref>Beckett 2005,[https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA153 p.153]</ref> This encouraged more applicants, with Lisburn and Ballymena being joined by [[Carrickfergus]], [[Craigavon]], [[Coleraine]], and [[Newry]].<ref name="beckett-170"/> Surprisingly, Lisburn and Newry were both successful, prompting allegations of political expediency, since Lisburn is strongly [[Protestantism in Ireland|Protestant]] and Newry strongly [[Catholicism in Ireland|Catholic]].<ref name="beckett-170"/> Ballymena representatives were aggrieved, and there were claims that Lisburn, as a suburb of Belfast, ought to be ineligible.<ref name="beckett-170">Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA175 p.175]</ref> [[Sinn Féin]] members of [[Newry and Mourne District Council]] were opposed to Newry's city status because of the connection to the [[British monarchy]]; other councillors welcomed the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newryandmourne.gov.uk/general_council/pdf/19%20March%202002.pdf |title=D.D.84./2002 – CITY STATUS |date=19 March 2002 |work=Minutes of District Development Committee Meeting |publisher=Newry and Mourne District Council |pages=4–7 |accessdate=23 May 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

===Current list===
None of the new cities for the 2012 [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] were Northern Irish.<ref name="bbc17364651"/> Thus the five recognised cities in Northern Ireland are [[Armagh]], [[Belfast]], [[Derry]], [[Lisburn]], and [[Newry]].<ref name="beckett-185">Beckett 2005, p.185</ref><ref name="doeni2015"/> The [[districts of Northern Ireland|local government districts]] named after two of the new cities were granted a corresponding change of name: from "Armagh District" to "[[Armagh City and District Council|Armagh City and District]]",<ref>{{cite journal |date=15 September 1995 |title=Change of District Name (Armagh) Order (Northern Ireland) 1995 |journal=[[Belfast Gazette]] |issue=5656 |page=804 |url=http://www.belfast-gazette.co.uk/issues/5656/pages/804}}</ref> and from "Lisburn Borough" to "[[Lisburn City Council|Lisburn City]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/sr/sr2002/20020231.htm |title=Change of District Name (Lisburn Borough) Order (Northern Ireland) 2002 |date=5 July 2002 |publisher=Office of Public Sector Information |accessdate=23 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206141412/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/Sr/sr2002/20020231.htm |archivedate= 6 December 2007 |df= }}</ref> just as the older cities had [[Belfast City Council]] and [[Derry City Council]]. [[Newry and Mourne District Council|Newry and Mourne district]]'s name did not use the word "city". In 2014–2015, the number of districts was [[Reform of local government in Northern Ireland|reduced from 26 to 11]] by merging all except Belfast and Derry with neighbouring ones. The successor districts inherited city status where applicable: those linked to a charter (Belfast, Derry, Lisburn) by request of its council, and those not linked to a charter (Armagh, Newry) automatically.<ref name="doeni2015">{{cite web|url=http://www.doeni.gov.uk/charters_and_status_-_consultation_document.pdf#page=10 |title=Draft Local Government (Transitional, Incidental, Consequential and Supplemental Provisions) Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2014: Charters and Status: Consultation Document|date=20 October 2014|author=DOENI ([[Department of the Environment (Northern Ireland)]])|accessdate=8 January 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423210032/http://www.doeni.gov.uk/charters_and_status_-_consultation_document.pdf#page=10|archivedate=23 April 2015|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/nisr/2015/125/regulation/3/made|title=The Local Government (Transitional, Incidental, Consequential and Supplemental Provisions) Regulations (Northern Ireland) 2015|date=5 March 2015|work=[[Legislation.gov.uk]]|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref> This is reflected in the names of [[Lisburn and Castlereagh City Council]] and [[Armagh, Banbridge and Craigavon District Council|Armagh City, Banbridge and Craigavon Borough Council]], but not in that of [[Newry, Mourne and Down District Council]].

==Republic of Ireland==
{{See also|Local government in the Republic of Ireland}}
The [[Local Government (Ireland) Act 1898]] abolished the corporate counties of the city of [[Kilkenny]] and the towns of Galway and [[Drogheda]] (and [[Carrickfergus]] in [[Ulster]]). The Act redesignated the other corporate counties as [[county borough]]s. After [[Partition of Ireland|Partition]], four of these were in the [[Irish Free State]], which later became the [[Republic of Ireland]]. Galway was made a fifth county borough in 1985.<ref name="galway-1985">[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1985/en/act/pub/0007/print.html Local Government (Reorganisation) Act, 1985] [[Irish Statute Book]]</ref> The [[Local Government Act 2001]] redesignates the five county boroughs as cities.<ref>Local Government Act, 2001 §10(4)(b)</ref> These cities, like the county boroughs before them, are almost identical in power and function to the [[counties of Ireland|administrative counties]]. The five administrative cities are [[Cork (city)|Cork]], Dublin, [[Galway]], [[Limerick]], and [[Waterford]].<ref>Local Government Act, 2001; Schedule 5, Part 2</ref>

The [[Local Government Reform Act 2014]] merged [[Limerick City Council]] and [[Limerick County Council]] into [[Limerick City and County Council]], and [[Waterford City Council]] and [[Waterford County Council]] into [[Waterford City and County Council]], with effect from the [[Irish local elections, 2014|2014 local elections]].<ref>
Local Government Reform Act 2014:
* sec.12(1) [amending sec.10(2) of the Local Government Act 2001] 
* sec.12(2) [adding Part 3 to Schedule 5 of the Local Government Act 2001]</ref> Each of the two merged local government areas is termed a "city and county".<ref>Local Government Reform Act 2014, sec 9(1)(a)(ii) and 9(1)(c)(ii)</ref> The changes are "without prejudice to the continued use of the description city in relation to Limerick and to Waterford".<ref>Local Government Reform Act 2014, sec.12(1) [amending sec.10(6)(b) of the Local Government Act 2001]</ref> Within each "city and county", the [[municipal district (Ireland)|municipal district]] which contains the city is styled a "metropolitan district" ({{lang|ga|Ceantar Cathrach}} in Irish).<ref>Local Government Reform Act 2014, sec.19 [insertion into Local Government Act 2001 of Section 22A(2)(a)]</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environ.ie/en/Publications/LocalGovernment/Administration/FileDownLoad,42666,en.pdf#page=9|pages=9–10|title=Local Government Arrangements in Cork|author=Cork Local Government Committee|date=September 2015|publisher=[[Department of the Environment, Community and Local Government]]|accessdate=8 September 2015}}
</ref>

===Dublin===
The [[Constitution of Ireland]] adopted in 1937 prescribes that the [[Oireachtas]] must meet, and the [[President of Ireland|President]] must reside, "in or near the City of Dublin"; the only occurrences of "city" in the Constitution.<ref>Art 12.11.1°, Art 15.1.3° {{cite web |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/en/constitution/index.html#article12_11_1 |title=Constitution of Ireland |publisher=Attorney General of Ireland |accessdate=17 October 2013 |work=Irish Statute Book }}</ref> In fact [[Leinster House]] and [[Áras an Uachtaráin]] are within the municipal limits of the city. The formula "in or near the City of Dublin" had occurred in earlier statutes, including [[James Butler, 1st Duke of Ormonde|Ormonde]]'s Articles of Peace of 1649<ref>Historical Collections of Private Passages of State, Weighty Matters in Law [https://books.google.com/books?id=TVtFAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA405&ots=ZpzJq7-uuK&dq=%22in%20or%20near%20the%20City%20of%20Dublin%22&pg=PA405#v=onepage&q=%22in%20or%20near%20the%20City%20of%20Dublin%22&f=false Part 4 Vol 1 p.415] John Rushworth, London, 1701</ref> and the [[Constitution of the Irish Free State|1922 Constitution]].<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1922/en/act/pub/0001/print.html Constitution of the Irish Free State (Saorstát Eireann) Act, 1922] Irish Statute Book</ref>

===Galway===
[[Galway]]'s status as a city was for long debatable.<ref>Beckett 2005, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqSSOyjBEoC&pg=PA16 p.16]</ref> Its nickname was "the city of the Tribes", but in British times it was legally a town, and its [[county corporate]] was the "county of the town of Galway".<ref>Parl Gazz Irl 1846 [https://books.google.com/books?id=4iK5_B7W1xIC&pg=PA237 Vol.2 p.237]</ref> Its 1484 charter grants [[Mayor of Galway|its Corporation's head]] the title of Mayor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galwaycity.ie/AllServices/YourCouncil/HistoryofTheCityCouncil/ |title=History of The City Council |publisher=Galway City Council |accessdate=15 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213052446/http://www.galwaycity.ie/AllServices/YourCouncil/HistoryofTheCityCouncil/ |archivedate=13 December 2009 |df= }}</ref> but so did the charters of [[Clonmel]] and [[Drogheda]],<ref>Municipal Corporations (Ireland) Act 1840, Schedule A</ref> as well as the charters extinguished in 1840 of [[Carrickfergus]], [[Coleraine]], [[Wexford]], and [[Youghal]],<ref>Municipal Corporations (Ireland) Act 1840, Schedule B</ref> none of which claimed the title of "city".

Galway was nevertheless intermittently described as a city; [[John Speed]]'s 1610 map of "[[Connacht|Connaugh]]" includes a plan of "the Citie of Galway".<ref>{{cite book|last=Abbott|first=T. K. |title=Catalogue of the manuscripts in the Library of Trinity college, Dublin, to which is added a list of the Fagel collection of maps in the same library|url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofmanus00trinrich#page/238/mode/2up|year=1900|publisher=Hodges Figgis |location=Dublin |pages=238, No.70 |chapter=Maps, Plans, etc., principally relating to Ireland (some printed).}}</ref> In ''[[Hardiman's History of Galway|The history of the town and county of the town of Galway]]'' (1820), [[James Hardiman]] generally describes it as a town. However, his account of the 1651 map commissioned by [[Ulick Burke, 1st Marquess of Clanricarde|Clanricarde]] concludes that at the time Galway "was universally acknowledged to be the most perfect city in the kingdom".<ref name="Hardiman1820">{{cite book|last=Hardiman|first=James|title=The history of the town and county of the town of Galway|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lv8HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA29|accessdate=16 May 2010|year=1820|location=Dublin |page=29}}</ref> [[Robert Wilson Lynd]] in 1912 referred to "Galway city – technically, it is only Galway town —".<ref>{{cite book |title=Rambles in Ireland |first=Robert |last=Lynd |year=1912 |publisher=D. Estes & company |page=14 }}</ref> The Local Government (Galway) Act, 1937, describes it as the "Town of Galway" and creates a municipal government called the "Borough of Galway".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1937/en/act/prv/0003/print.html Local Government (Galway) Act, 1937] Irish Statute Book</ref> On the other hand, the Aran Islands (Transport) Act, 1936, regulates steamships travelling "between the City of Galway and the [[Aran Islands]]";<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1936/en/act/pub/0036/sec0002.html Aran Islands (Transport) Act, 1936 §2 Contracts for steamer service to the Aran Islands.] Irish Statute Book</ref> also, legislators debating the passage of the 1937 Act frequently referred to Galway as a "city".<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/seanad/1934/07/11/00003.asp Seanad debates Vol.16 cc.1773–83]</ref><ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/1937/06/09/00010.asp Dáil debates Vol.68 cc.109–112]</ref>

When the borough was made a [[county borough]] in 1985, the Borough Council became the "City Council" and it acquired its own "[[Chief executive (Irish local government)|City Manager]]".<ref name="galway-1985"/> This was not presented as the acquiring of city status; [[Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government|Minister for the Environment]] [[Liam Kavanagh]] said it was "the extension of the Galway City boundary and for upgrading of that city to the status of county borough".<ref>[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0356/D.0356.198503140004.html Local Government (Reorganisation) Bill, 1985: Second Stage.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609124923/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0356/D.0356.198503140004.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 356 – 14 March 1985</ref>

===Kilkenny===
The only city in the Republic which was not a county borough was [[Kilkenny]]. The original version of the 2001 Act would have reclassified as "towns" all "boroughs" which were not county boroughs, including Kilkenny.<ref>[http://www.oireachtas.ie/documents/bills28/bills/2000/2300/b2300.pdf Local Government Bill, 2000 ''As initiated''] Oireachtas</ref> This drew objections from Kilkenny's borough councillors, and from [[Teachta Dála|TDs]] [[Phil Hogan]] and [[John J. McGuinness]].<ref>[http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/0538/D.0538.200106130019.html Local Government Bill, 2000: Second Stage (Resumed).] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606110451/http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/0538/D.0538.200106130019.html |date= 6 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 538 – 13 June 2001</ref> Accordingly, a clause was added to the bill:<ref>Local Government Act, 2001 §10(7)</ref>
<blockquote>This section is without prejudice to the continued use of the description city in relation to Kilkenny, to the extent that that description was used before the establishment day and is not otherwise inconsistent with this Act.</blockquote>
The Act also states:<ref>Local Government Act, 2001 §11(16)</ref>
<blockquote>Subject to this Act, royal charters and letters patent relating to local authorities shall continue to apply for ceremonial and related purposes in accordance with local civic tradition but shall otherwise cease to have effect.</blockquote>
[[Minister of State (Ireland)|Minister of State]] [[Tom Kitt]] explained these provisions as follows:<ref>[http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/S/0167/S.0167.200107110004.html Local Government Bill, 2000: Committee Stage.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606110535/http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/S/0167/S.0167.200107110004.html |date= 6 June 2011 }} Seanad Éireann – Volume 167 – 11 July 2001</ref>
<blockquote>New provisions to recognise the term "city" to describe Kilkenny in line with long-established historical and municipal practice were brought in. Kilkenny was reconstituted as a borough corporation under the Municipal Corporations Act, 1840, as were Clonmel, Drogheda and Sligo. Section 2 of the 1840 Act specifically provided that Kilkenny is a borough which is still the current legal position in local government law. Traditionally, however, Kilkenny had been referred to as a city and this has its roots in local usage, deriving from a 17th century charter. It has not been a city in terms of local government law for at least 160 years.<br />
As I have indicated, the Bill as published specifically provides that local charters can continue for ceremonial or related purposes, thereby safeguarding local tradition and practice. There was, therefore, no difficulty in Kilkenny continuing with this long-established tradition. However, Kilkenny Corporation indicated that it was concerned that the existing provisions in the Bill would not maintain the status quo in addition to concerns with the other boroughs that the term "town" was some form of diminution of status. In view of these concerns the Minister [ [[Noel Dempsey]] ] indicated that he would include a provision in the Bill to specifically recognise the traditional usage of the term "city" to describe Kilkenny. For the first time ever in the Local Government Act the unique position of Kilkenny is being recognised in local government law.<br />
The Minister honoured in full his commitment on Kilkenny and delivered on what the deputation from Kilkenny sought. It was never intended that Kilkenny would be a city such as Dublin or Cork. All Kilkenny wanted was to be allowed to continue to use the term "city" in recognition of its ancient tradition. The deputation expressed its satisfaction to the Minister on his proposal.</blockquote>
In 2002, Phil Hogan (a [[Fine Gael]] TD) asked for "full city status" for Kilkenny;<ref>[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0550/D.0550.200203200346.html Written Answers. – City Status.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609125142/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0550/D.0550.200203200346.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 550 – 20 March 2002</ref> in 2009 he said "Kilkenny has lost its City status courtesy of [[Fianna Fáil]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kilkennypeople.ie/news/Jobs-funding-under-threat-as.5480013.jp |title=Jobs, funding under threat as Bord Snip gets set to slash |last=Keane |first=Sean |date=24 July 2009 |work=Kilkenny People |accessdate=15 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090729035702/http://www.kilkennypeople.ie/news/Jobs-funding-under-threat-as.5480013.jp |archivedate=29 July 2009 |df= }}</ref>

The Local Government Reform Act 2014 established new municipal districts throughout the state and to abolish all the boroughs, including Kilkenny. Whereas the municipal district encompassing other boroughs are styled "the Borough District of Sligo [or Drogheda/Wexford/Clonmel]", that encompassing Kilkenny is styled "the Municipal District of Kilkenny City".<ref>Local Government Reform Act 2014, sec.19 [insertion into Local Government Act 2001 of Section 22A(2)(b) and 22A(2)(c)]</ref>

===National Spatial Strategy===
{{main article|National Spatial Strategy}}
The National Spatial Strategy (NSS) for 2002–2020 planned to manage urban sprawl by identifying certain urban centres outside Dublin as areas for concentrated growth. The NSS report calls the regional centres "gateways" and the sub-regional centres "hubs".<ref name="nss-38">NSS 2002, p.38</ref> It does not call them "cities", but among the features it lists for "Gateways" are "City level range of theatres, arts and sports centres and public spaces/parks." and "City-scale water and waste management services."<ref name="nss-40">NSS 2002, p.40</ref> It also gives a target population for a gateway of over 100,000, including the suburban hinterland.<ref name="nss-40"/>

The report describes Cork, Limerick/[[Shannon, County Clare|Shannon]], Galway and Waterford, as  "existing gateways" and identifies four "new national level gateways": [[Dundalk]], [[Sligo]], and two "linked" gateways
[[Letterkenny]]/([[Derry]]), and [[Athlone]]/[[Tullamore]]/[[Mullingar]].<ref name="nss-38"/> The campaigns of Sligo and Dundalk for city status have referenced their status as regional gateways. The "[[Midlands Region, Ireland|Midlands]] Gateway", a [[wikt:polycentric|polycentric]] zone based on Tullamore, Athlone, and Mullingar, has occasionally been described as constituting a new or future city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/unsorted/property/new-athlone-retail-complex-to-tap-into-midlands-new-wealth-255656.html|title=New Athlone retail complex to tap into Midlands' new wealth |date=22 June 2005|work=[[Irish Independent]]|quote=the government's National Spatial Strategy [creates] a major city by linking the towns of Athlone, Mullingar and Tullamore.|accessdate=19 May 2010|location=Dublin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2005/0415/spatialstrategy.html|title=Calls for re-opening of railway line|date=15 April 2005|work=[[RTÉ.ie]]|quote=Delegates were also told that the gateway towns of Athlone, Tullamore and Mullingar would constitute a joint city with a population of over 100,000 people within the next 30 years.|publisher=RTÉ|accessdate=19 May 2010}}</ref> A 2008 study by [[Dublin Institute of Technology]] concluded that the growth in population of the designated gateways was far less than had been planned.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/sligoweekender/2008/02/05/story34779.asp |title=Sligo won't ever be a city, says Dublin-based report |date=5 February 2005 |work=Sligo Weekender |accessdate=21 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622084401/http://archives.tcm.ie/sligoweekender/2008/02/05/story34779.asp |archivedate=22 June 2011 |df= }}</ref>

===Prospective cities===
{{See also|List of towns in the Republic of Ireland by population}}
Local councillors and [[Teachta Dála|TD]]s from several towns have raised the possibility of gaining city status. Prior to the 2001 Act, these suggestions were a matter of simple prestige.  Since the 2001 Act, the suggestions sometimes relate to the administrative functions of county-equivalent cities and sometimes to the ceremonial title. The [[Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government|Minister for the Environment]], who is responsible for local government, has not entertained these suggestions,<ref name="odowd"/><ref name="coc"/> and has said "A modernised legal framework and structures at both regional and local level are now in place ... I have no proposals for amending legislation, which would be necessary to establish new city councils."<ref name="noonan"/>

====Drogheda====
The possibility of [[Drogheda]] gaining city status was raised in Dáil questions by [[Gay Mitchell]] in 2005,<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/2005/06/28/00032.asp 28 June 2005 Dáil debates 2005 p.32]</ref> [[Michael Noonan (Fine Gael politician)|Michael Noonan]] in 2007<ref name="noonan">[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0635/D.0635.200704050109.html Written Answers. – City Status.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609124423/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0635/D.0635.200704050109.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 635 – 5 April 2007</ref> and by [[Fergus O'Dowd]] in 2007<ref name="odowd">[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0636/D.0636.200704240736.html Written Answers. – City Status.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609124434/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0636/D.0636.200704240736.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 636 – 24 April 2007</ref> and 2010.<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/2010/05/11/00214.asp Dáil debates 11 May 2010 p.214]</ref> The Borough Council's draft development plan for 2011–17 does not mention city status,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Drogheda-Borough-Council/Draft_Drogheda_Borough_Council_Development_Plan_2011-2017.html |title=Draft Drogheda Borough Council Development Plan 2011–2017 |year=2009 |publisher=Drogheda Borough Council |accessdate=22 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430133712/http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Drogheda-Borough-Council/Draft_Drogheda_Borough_Council_Development_Plan_2011-2017.html |archivedate=30 April 2010 |df= }}</ref> although the manager's summary of public submissions reported backing for city status for the greater Drogheda area, incorporating adjacent areas in Counties [[County Louth|Louth]] and [[County Meath|Meath]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Murray|first=Conn|title=Drogheda Borough Council Review of Development Plan 2005–2011: Managers Report prepared under Section 11 (4) of the Planning and Development Act 2000 in relation to submissions received.|url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Drogheda-Borough-Council/Draft_Development_Plan_2011-2017/Drogheda_Managers_Report.pdf#page=8|date=1 September 2009|page=5|chapter=Theme 1 : Development Strategy.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621233519/http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Drogheda-Borough-Council/Draft_Development_Plan_2011-2017/Drogheda_Managers_Report.pdf#page=8|archivedate=21 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, a "Drogheda City Status Campaign" was launched,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/droghedaindependent/news/drogheda-now-regarded-as-major-city-in-all-but-name-27150612.html|title=Drogheda now regarded as major city in all but name|last=Murphy|first=Hubert|date=20 October 2010|work=[[Drogheda Independent]] |accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref> and in March 2012, Drogheda Borough Council passed a resolution, "That the members of Drogheda Borough Council from this day forward give their consent and approval to the people of Drogheda referring to Drogheda as the City of Drogheda".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Drogheda_Borough_Council/Minutes_of_Statutory_Meetings/2012/Minutes_of_Council_Meeting_-_March_2012_1_.doc |title=51/12 Notice of Motion – The Mayor, Councillor K. Callan. |work=Minutes of Council Meeting of Drogheda Borough Council held in the Governor's House, Millmount, Drogheda, on 5th March, 2012, at 7.00 p.m. |accessdate=9 September 2013 |format=[[MS Word]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/droghedaindependent/news/drogheda-city-status-group-to-meet-with-minister-hogan-27165712.html|title=Drogheda City Status group to meet with Minister Hogan|date=11 April 2012 |work=Drogheda Independent |accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref>

====Dundalk====
[[Dundalk]]'s development plan for 2003–09 stated "Dundalk, in order to fulfil its potential as a regional growth centre, should, in the near future achieve City Status, to acknowledge its present role and to enable its future growth as a regional gateway."<ref name="dundalk-plan-2003">{{cite book |chapterurl=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Corporate-Plans/1-Introduction-and-Context.pdf#page=8 |format=PDF |title=Dundalk & Environs Development Plan |chapter=1 Introduction & Context |page=8 |publisher=Dundalk Town Council |accessdate=19 May 2010}}</ref> Michael Noonan asked a question in the Dáil in 2007.<ref name="noonan"/> Dundalk's draft development plan for 2009–15 seeks to develop the "Newry–Dundalk Twin City Region" with [[Newry]], which is nearby across [[Republic of Ireland – United Kingdom border|the border]].<ref name="dundalk-plan-2009">{{cite book |format=PDF |url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Dundalk_Town_Council/Development_Plan_2009-2015/Dundalk_And_Environs_Development_Plan_2009-2015.pdf#page=44 |page=32 |chapter=3.2.3 Economic Corridor |title=Dundalk And Environs Development Plan 2009–2015 |year=2009 |publisher=Dundalk Town Council |accessdate=19 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621233156/http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Dundalk_Town_Council/Development_Plan_2009-2015/Dundalk_And_Environs_Development_Plan_2009-2015.pdf#page=44 |archivedate=21 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Chief executive (Irish local government)|county manager]] of [[County Louth]] made a summary of public submissions on the plan, which predicted [[Dundalk Institute of Technology]] being upgraded to university status would help to win city status.<ref>{{cite book|format=PDF|url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Dundalk_Town_Council/Draft_Development_Plan_2009-2015/Manager%27s-Report-in-Relation-to-submissions.pdf#page=11|title=Managers Report prepared under Section 11 (4) of the Planning and Development Act 2000 in relation to submissions received.|date=August 2008|publisher=Dundalk Town Council|pages=7 Theme 1 : Economic Strategy b) Achieving City Status:|accessdate=19 May 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812211056/http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Publications/Development-Plans/Dundalk_Town_Council/Draft_Development_Plan_2009-2015/Manager%27s-Report-in-Relation-to-submissions.pdf#page=11|archivedate=12 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

====Sligo====
[[John Perry (Irish politician)|John Perry]] raised an [[adjournment debate]] in 1999 calling for [[Sligo]] to be declared a "millennium city", stating:<ref name="sligo1999">[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0510/D.0510.199911090027.html Adjournment Debate. – City Status for Sligo.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609124412/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0510/D.0510.199911090027.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 510 – 9 November 1999</ref>
<blockquote>While the Government will probably say Sligo can call itself a city, an official declaration by the Government to declare Sligo the millennium city will confer an official status on it. The word 'city' has a certain meaning for investors. ... The requirement for a town to be called a city is that it be a seat of government or a cathedral town. Sligo is sometimes called a town and sometimes a city. This leads to confusion and the region falls between both stools. An official declaration of Sligo as a millennium city would have major significance for the entire area. The word city has a certain meaning for investors. It presumes a certain level of services and a status towards which the world reacts very favourably. The Fitzpatrick report established Sligo as a future growth centre. Even officials of Sligo Corporation are confused because in certain instances Sligo is called a town and in others a city.</blockquote>

[[Declan Bree]], mayor of the town in 2005, advocated "Sligo gaining city status similar to Limerick, Galway and Waterford."<ref name="bree2005">{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/sligoweekender/2005/06/28/story23635.asp |title=Sligo seeks to push out towards city status |last=Bree |first=Declan |date=28 June 2005 |work=Sligo Weekender |accessdate=15 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629122454/http://archives.tcm.ie/sligoweekender/2005/06/28/story23635.asp |archivedate=29 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> The town council and county council held meetings to plan an expansion of the borough boundaries with a view to enhancing the prospects for such a change.<ref name="bree2005"/>

The main building of Sligo Borough Council is called "City Hall".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sligoborough.ie/Services/Architecture/CityHall/ |title=The Story of the City Hall |publisher=Sligo Borough Council |accessdate=3 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731050820/http://www.sligoborough.ie/Services/Architecture/CityHall/ |archivedate=31 July 2013 |df= }}</ref>

====Swords====
[[Michael Kennedy (Dublin politician)|Michael Kennedy]], [[Teachta Dála|TD]] for [[Dublin North (Dáil constituency)|Dublin North]], stated in 2007 that "[[Fingal County Council]] is planning to confer city status on our county town of [[Swords, County Dublin|Swords]] in the next 15 to 20 years as its population grows to 100,000."<ref>[http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0641/D.0641.200711140013.html Local Government (Roads Functions) Bill 2007: Second Stage (Resumed).] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609125105/http://www.oireachtas-debates.gov.ie/D/0641/D.0641.200711140013.html |date= 9 June 2011 }} Dáil Éireann – Volume 641 – 14 November 2007</ref> In May 2008, the Council published "Your Swords, an Emerging City, Strategic Vision 2035", with a vision of Swords as "an emerging green city of 100,000 people."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fingalcoco.ie/Planning/PlanningItemsOnDisplay/PlanningItemsPreviouslyonDisplay/L-ZPreviouslyonDisplay2004-2009/SwordsDraftVariation-June08/FileDownload,20172,en.pdf#page=1 |page=1 |title=Your Swords, an Emerging City, Strategic Vision 2035 |publisher=Fingal County Council |date=May 2008 |accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref>

====Tallaght====
A campaign to have [[Tallaght]] given city status was launched in 2003 by Eamonn Maloney, a local member of [[South Dublin]] county council.<ref name="times-tallaght">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/ireland/article7061084.ece?print=yes&randnum=1151003209000|title=Tallaght relaunches fight for city status|last=McInerney|first=Sarah|date=14 March 2010|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|accessdate=15 May 2010}}</ref> It is supported by the Tallaght Area Committee, comprising 10 of the 26 county councillors.<ref name="times-tallaght"/> Advantages envisaged by the campaign's website include having a dedicated [[Industrial Development Authority]] branch office for attracting investment, and facilitating the upgrade of [[Institute of Technology, Tallaght]] to university status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tallaghtcitycampaign.com/about-the-campaign.html |title=About The Campaign |publisher=Tallaght City Campaign |accessdate=21 May 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716191229/http://www.tallaghtcitycampaign.com/about-the-campaign.html |archivedate=16 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> When [[Charlie O'Connor]] asked about city status for "Tallaght, [[Dublin 24]]" in 2007, the minister had "no plans to re-designate [[South Dublin]] County Council as a city council, or to establish Tallaght as a separate city authority".<ref name="coc">[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/2007/09/26/00673.asp Written Answers. – Local Government Reform.] Dáil Éireann – Volume 638 – 26 September 2007</ref> O'Connor said later "The only problem I can see is our close proximity to Dublin".<ref name="times-tallaght"/> The head of the local [[chamber of commerce]] said in 2010, "If Tallaght was anywhere else in the country, it would have been a city years ago. We already have the population, [[Tallaght Hospital|the hospital]] and the third-level institution. If we're missing something, someone needs to tell us, clarify what the criteria [are], and we'll get it."<ref name="times-tallaght"/>

